Saoul of corruption
My friend Boris was leaving my place, drunk.
I suggested to him not to drive.
He asked me why.
"You've been drinking," I said, "aren't you afraid of the police?"
Boris replied to me: « No, I have a document featuring Benjamin Franklin, it's always useful.
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police take bribes, but I was worried that Boris would encounter a policeman who wasn't corrupt.
« Impossible, » Boris declared, « to get into the traffic division of the police force, you have to buy your chief's silence.
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your chief's silence?
The half of drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
Idiots who try to do things by the book get bogged down in administrative hassles.
For 100 dollars, you can drive in the city without brakes!
Cronyism and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before Lenin's October Revolution and after.
But never at the record levels we see today.
Tout le monde accepte les pots-de-vin, partout et pour tout.
Les seuls qui n'en acceptent pas sont ceux à qui l'on n'en offre pas, selon Boris.
La corruption s'épanouit dans la plupart des institutions, et la lutte contre la corruption se finit toujours par une catastrophe ou un abandon.
La police, les procureurs, les douaniers et même le Kremlin : personne nulle part n'est immunisé.
Récemment, j'étais en visite dans un village de datchas dans l'une des plus jolies banlieues de Moscou.
This was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious houses decorated with such poor taste, I wondered who owned them and heard that one belonged to an assistant mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of Moscow's procurator.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax service official.
Corruption now poses a more serious threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police who sell arms and supplies to the rebels.
Recently, Russian television showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that carried 120 kilograms of explosives used in the theater Dubrovka siege, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a wet acid-soaked cloth to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A pointless precaution.
No one controls the buses anymore today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, recounted being stopped 50 times along his route, for the same reason each time.
A policeman came up to him and asked: "Do you know what the price is?", and the driver replied: "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without the bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, or even for entire days on the route.
The war against Chechnya continues without end not only because Chechen rebels have allies in Al-Qaeda and all 'international terrorism', but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the military, civilians who accept bribes and thieves, who first tax or simply rob Chechen civilians, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide them with maps indicating where minefields are, and supply rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk bombings, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where did they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no armories.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels do have ammunition supplies, so the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not just weapons: some young officers even sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no fight against this scourge has been launched.
Harsher penalties for corruption?
This would only increase the cost of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are corrupt themselves.
Thus, those called 'ordinary people' consider this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say about their mayor, "Yes of course, he steals, but look at everything he has done for the city!"
The ordinary people also do not like honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the controller both benefit from this system.
A truthful old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The controller stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not admitted to the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy a clerk in the army, and he will remove your son's name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare your son unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive under the influence, speed excessively, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to take the blame with the police.
Alexander Menchikov, Minister of Peter the Great, understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the disgusted Tsar Peter decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov responded: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Since then, the situation has worsened over the centuries.
Removing corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the progression of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
